  "prompt": "Is Governor of RBI (Reserve Bank of India) a constitutional post?",
  "response": "The Governor of the Reserve Bank of India (RBI) is not a constitutional post in the same way that positions like the President of India or the Chief Justice of India are. Instead, the Governor of the RBI is appointed under the Reserve Bank of India Act, 1934. This act outlines the powers, responsibilities, and structure of the RBI, including the appointment and tenure of the Governor.\n\nWhile the position is not mentioned in the Constitution of India, it is a significant and influential role in the Indian financial system, responsible for regulating the issue of banknotes, maintaining monetary stability, and overseeing the financial sector in India. The appointment is made by the Central Government of India.",
